# Vercel Web Analytics Installation Report

## Summary
Successfully installed and configured Vercel Web Analytics for the DriftGuard web application following the latest official Vercel documentation.

## Changes Made

### 1. Package Installation
- **Added dependency**: `@vercel/analytics` version `^2.0.1`
- **Package manager**: pnpm (as per project configuration)
- **Installation method**: Used `pnpm add @vercel/analytics -w` to install at workspace root

### 2. Code Integration
**Modified file**: `apps/web/app/layout.tsx`
- Added import: `import { Analytics } from "@vercel/analytics/next";`
- Added `<Analytics />` component to the root layout's `<body>` element, placed after all provider wrappers but before closing `</body>` tag
- **Framework**: Next.js 15 with App Router
- **Integration method**: Followed the official Next.js App Router pattern from Vercel documentation

### 3. File Changes
- `apps/web/app/layout.tsx` - Added Analytics component import and rendered component
- `apps/web/package.json` - Added @vercel/analytics dependency
- `apps/web/pnpm-lock.yaml` - Updated lockfile with new dependency tree

## Implementation Details

### Framework Context
- Project uses Next.js 15 with App Router pattern
- Root layout is located at `apps/web/app/layout.tsx`
- Layout includes multiple providers: I18nProvider, AuthProvider, PostHogProvider
- Analytics component placed at the end of body to not interfere with existing providers

### Component Placement
The `<Analytics />` component was strategically placed:
- Inside the `<body>` tag
- After all content and provider wrappers
- Before the closing `</body>` tag
- This ensures proper initialization without blocking critical rendering

## Verification

### Build Status
✅ **Build successful** - Ran `pnpm build` and completed without errors
- All pages compiled successfully
- No build-time warnings or errors
- Bundle sizes within acceptable limits

### Linting Status
✅ **Linting passed** - Ran `pnpm lint` with zero errors or warnings
- No ESLint errors introduced
- Code follows project conventions

### Dependency Management
✅ **Lockfile updated** - pnpm-lock.yaml properly updated with:
- @vercel/analytics and all its dependencies
- Preserved existing dependency tree integrity

## Next Steps for Deployment

To enable Web Analytics on Vercel:
1. Deploy this change to your Vercel project
2. Navigate to your project's Analytics section in the Vercel dashboard
3. Click "Enable" to activate Web Analytics
4. After deployment, verify tracking by checking browser Network tab for `/_vercel/insights/*` requests

## Documentation Reference
Installation followed the official Vercel documentation at:
https://vercel.com/docs/analytics/quickstart

The implementation uses the Next.js App Router integration pattern as documented.
